1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6 {This variation has gained
popularity recently. I have played this line myself as well, and can't
complain about the results so far.} 6. e3 ({Another option is a typical
sacrifice of the Pc4 pawn:} 6. e4 Bb4 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bd2 b5 {White often gets a
long-term compensation for the pawn.}) 6... c5 {In fact, the position
transposes to the Queen's Gambit Accepted where Black has lost a tempo by
playing c7-c6 and then c6-c5. White's extra tempo is the move a2-a4. On the
one hand it helps White to seize space on the queenside. On the other hand, it
weakens the b4 square and this is what Black is counting on. In future, this
square might be used for a knight transfer Nb8-c6-b4 to a key blockading d5
square.} 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 (8... Be7 9. Qe2 (9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 {
leads to an equal endgame.}) 9... cxd4 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Nxd4 Qc7 12. Nxc6 bxc6
13. a5 e5 14. e4 Rb8 15. h3 Bc5 16. Na4 Bd4 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Qxa5 19. Nc5
Qc7 20. Qa3 a6 21. Qc3 Nd7 22. b4 Re8 23. Nxd7 Bxd7 24. Rxa6 $14 {1-0
Gustafsson,J (2603)-Kharitonov,A (2526)/Plovdiv BUL 2008/The Week in Chess 704
(55)}) 9. exd4 Be7 10. Bg5 (10. Be3 {is toothless. The bishop is passive on e3.
} O-O 11. Ne5 Nb4 12. a5 Bd7 13. d5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nbxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5
Bc8 $1 $11 {1/2-1/2 Leko,P (2741)-Kramnik,V (2770)/Brissago 2004}) (10. Qe2 O-O
(10... Nxd4 $2 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Nb5 Qd8 13. Bf4 $18) 11. Rd1 Nb4 12. Bg5 h6 $1
(12... Bd7 13. d5 $1 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nbxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5
h6 18. Rad1 hxg5 19. Rxd7 Qb6 $14 {1/2-1/2 Ivanchuk,V (2729)-Svidler,P (2765)/
Monte Carlo 2006 (46)}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Ne5 Qc7 15. Ng4 Be7 16. d5 exd5 17.
Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxg4 {1/2-1/2 Babula,V (2594)-Balogh,C (2575)/Graz AUT 2008/
The Week in Chess 698}) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Bd7 (11... h6 $6 {is very risky in
view of} 12. Bf4 Nb4 13. Qd2 Bd7 14. Bxh6 $1 Rc8 15. Bb3 gxh6 16. Qxh6 $40 {
1-0 Radjabov,T (2700)-Svidler,P (2765)/Linares 2006 (41)}) 12. Qd2 {It is
always a question for White where to put his queen. An alternative option is
12.Qe2 trying to press along the e-file and specifically on Pe6.} (12. Qe2 Nb4
13. Ne5 Kh8 (13... Bc6 $2 14. Nxf7 $1 {reveals the point of 12.Qe2.}) 14. Rad1
Bc6 15. h4 Nfd5 16. Qh5 {In this double-edged position a draw was agreed. 1/
2-1/2 Halkias,S (2580)-Postny,E (2598)/Zlatibor 2007/CBM 120 ext}) 12... Rc8
13. Rad1 (13. d5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 exd5 16. Bxd5 Bf5 17. Rad1 Qf6 18.
Qf4 Bc2 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. Rd2 Bxa4 $6 (20... Nb4 $1 $11) 21. Ne4 Kg7 22. Nc5
Bb5 23. Nxb7 $14 {1-0 Bekker Jensen,S (2393)-Rasmussen,K (2449)/Aalborg 2006/
CBM 111 ext (48)}) 13... Nb4 14. Ne5 {A novelty which was probably prepared by
Shirov before the game, as Svidler had already played this position as Black.
Instead, the breakthrough d4-d5 leads to massive simplifications and equality
in this case.} (14. d5 exd5 15. Bxd5 Bc6 16. Bxc6 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 Nxc6 18. Bxf6
Bxf6 19. Nd5 Rfd8 20. Nxf6+ gxf6 21. g3 Rxd2 22. Nxd2 Ne5 23. Kg2 Kg7 24. Nf3
Rc4 {1/2-1/2 Nielsen,P (2644)-Svidler,P (2765)/Monte Carlo 2006/CBM 111 ext})
14... Nbd5 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 (15... Bxf6 $6 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bxd5 Bxa4 18. Bxb7
Bxe5 19. Rxe5 Rc2 20. Qb4 Rxb2 21. Qxb2 Bxd1 22. Be4 $14) 16. d5 {This
thematic breakthrough is White's main weapon in these kind of positions with
an isolated pawn. However, Black can survive it.} Bb4 $1 17. dxe6 Bxe6 18. Qc2
(18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Qe2 Qe8 20. Nc4 Nd5 21. Nxd5 Bxe1 22. Nd6 Bxf2+ 23. Kh1 Qd7
24. Nxc8 exd5 25. Ne7+ Kh8 {can be dangerous only for White.}) 18... Qb6 19.
Bxe6 fxe6 {The Pe6 is obviously weak but, after the following exchange on c3
white's queenside pawns will become vulnerable as well. The position is equal.}
(19... Qxe6 $2 {loses an exchange in view of} 20. Nd7) 20. Nd3 (20. Rd3 Rfd8
21. Rde3 Bc5 22. R3e2 Bd4 23. Nf3 Rc6 $11) 20... Bxc3 21. bxc3 Nd5 22. c4 Nb4
23. Nxb4 Qxb4 $11 24. Re4 b5 $2 {This move actually blunders a pawn and can be
considered as a decisive mistake.} ({A simple move like} 24... Rcd8 {would
keep the position equal.}) 25. Rh4 {[%csl Rh7]} h6 (25... g6 26. axb5 Qxb5 27.
Qxg6+ hxg6 28. cxb5 {leads to a bad endgame for Black.}) 26. axb5 Qxb5 27. Rxh6
$1 {This is the refutation of 24...b5. Probably this punch was overlooked by
Svidler. Black loses a pawn without any compensation.} Qf5 (27... gxh6 $4 28.
Qg6+ $18 {[%csl Rb5]}) 28. Qxf5 exf5 (28... Rxf5 $2 29. Rxe6 Rxc4 {should be
lost for Black as White has three pawns against one on the kingside.}) 29. Rh4
{It is not so easy to state a clear verdict on this endgame but, it seems to
me that it is lost for Black.} f4 30. Rd4 Rb8 {Trying to activate the rook.
Another attempt was to push the a-pawn as quickly as possible.} (30... a5 31.
Rhxf4 Rxf4 32. Rxf4 a4 33. Rf3 Rxc4 (33... Ra8 34. Ra3 Kf7 35. Kf1 Ke6 36. Ke2
Kd6 37. Kd3 Kc5 38. Kc3 $18) 34. g3 Rb4 35. Rf5 {transfering the rook to a5.
After that White's pawn majority will decide the outcome.}) 31. h3 f3 (31... a5
32. Rhxf4 Rxf4 33. Rxf4 a4 34. c5 Ra8 35. Rc4 a3 36. Rc1 a2 37. Ra1 Kf7 38. Kf1
Ke6 39. Ke2 Kd5 40. Kd3 Kxc5 41. Kc3 Ra6 42. Kb3 Rg6 (42... Kd4 43. Rxa2 Rxa2
44. Kxa2 Kd3 45. h4 Ke2 46. h5 Kxf2 47. g4 $18) 43. g3 Rb6+ 44. Kxa2 Ra6+ 45.
Kb2 Rxa1 46. Kxa1 Kd4 47. h4 Ke4 48. Kb2 Kf3 49. h5 $1 Kg4 50. Kc3 Kxh5 51. Kd4
$18) 32. g4 Rb1+ ({Again,} 32... a5 {does not help} 33. Rh5 a4 34. Rd3 Rb1+ 35.
Kh2 Rf1 36. Rd2 Ra8 37. Kg3 a3 38. Ra2 $18 {[%csl Ra3,Rf3][%cal Gh5e5,Ge5e3]})
33. Kh2 Rf1 34. Rd2 Re8 {The last practical chance is to go for the Pf2.} 35.
Kg3 Re2 36. Rd8+ Kf7 37. Rd7+ $1 Kg6 ({After} 37... Ke6 38. Rxg7 Rexf2 39. Kf4
Kd6 40. Rh5 $1 {Black's king can't escape.}) 38. Rh8 Rexf2 {Black got the pawn
but, now his king left unprotected. White can build a mating net meanwhile,
his king will get a shelter on f4.} 39. Rg8 Rg2+ 40. Kf4 f2 41. Rgxg7+ Kf6 42.
Rh7 Ke6 43. Kg5 $1 {The threat 44.Rhe7 mate is unanswerable. Black resigned.}
1-0

